<article>
	<header>
	<h1>Tor Caldara 16S rRNA pyrotag from cDNA results</h1>
	<h4>by D. Giovannelli</h4>
	</header>

	<section>
	<h3>General info</h3>
	<p>The pyrotag was perfomed on the DATE by Mr. DNA sequencing facilities using the Bacterial primer couple 27f-338r. the extraction of totalRNA from the filaments preserved in RNAlater was performed by Sushmita Patwardhan on the DATE and converted to cDNA using random-hexamer witht he First Strand kit. The results have been re-analyzed using Qiime 1.6 and Greengenes database with the custom built pipeline on the 02-may-2013 by D. Giovannelli. </p>
	</section>

	<section>
	<h3>Results</h3>
	<p>A total of 3356 sequences passed quality check and chimera removal and were clustered in 419 unique OTUs.</p>

<table border="1" bordercolor="333" width="50%" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
	<tr>
		<td>Number of Sequences</td>
		<td>3356</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td>Number of unique OTUs</td>
		<td>419</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td>Shannon diversity (H')</td>
		<td>4.974</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td>Chao1 diversity estimator</td>
		<td>930.95 (@3,016 seq)</td>
	</tr>
</table>

<p>The sample is dominated by sequences classified as Gammaproteobacteria (60% of sequences). the entire diversity is dominated by a single cluster (OTU 229) containing 43.37% of sequences and classified as uncultured <em>Gammaproteobacteria</em>. The representing sequence is affiliated to <em>Siboglinidae sp.</em> associated bacterium partial 16S rRNA gene, clone W11_2 (blastn, <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/320202854" target_="blank">FR682107.2</a> 87% similarity) or using EzTaxon and getting the top four hits:</p>

<table border="1" bordercolor="333" width="50%" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
  <tr>
	<td>Species</td> 
	<td>Accession number</td>
	<td>Similarity</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
	<td><em>Thiorhodococcus minor</em></td> 
	<td>Y11316</td>
	<td>87.288%</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
	<td><em>Cocleimonas flava</em></td> 
	<td>AB495251</td> 	
	<td>87.238%</td> 
  </tr>
  <tr>
	<td><em>Thioprofundum lithotrophicum</em></td> 
	<td>AB468957</td> 	
	<td>87.002%</td> 	
  </tr>
  <tr>
	<td><em>Leucothrix mucor</em></td> 
	<td>X87277</td>	
	<td>86.975%</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>The second most abundant OTU (29% of total sequences) is related to the <em>Firmicutes Bacillales</em> order (OTU 170) and related to <em>Staphylococcus sp.</em> JY04 16S ribosomal RNA gene (blastn top hit, accession <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/EU798945.1" target_="blank">EU798945.1</a>, similarity 100%) isolated from and sewage from insulating material factory or <em>Staphylococcus cohnii</em> strain BDA10 (blastn second best, accession <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/HQ641334.1" target_="blank">HQ641334.1</a>, similarity 99%) isolated during a bacterial biodiversity study in a finfish larviculture system. <img src="TC_order.png" height="500" width="600" /></p>

<p>See the <a href="../output_plots/bar_charts.html" target="_blank">original diversity barplots</a> for more details. You can retrieve the original sequences of each OTUs from the <a href="../Qiime_report.html" target="_blank"> Representative fasta sequences of each OTU</a> link in the Qiime Report page.</p> 

<p>The obtained diversity tree are the following, colored according to consensus diversity obtained from the Qiime analysis. Left tree shows the full diversity. In the right tree branches were collapsed and coloured according to 80% branch composition consensus. For example the bottom branch was colored and classified as <em>Bacilli</em> because more than 80% of the branches were <em>Bacilli</em> and remaining where mostrly Uncultured Bacteria.</p>
<img src="../tree/tree_TC.png" height="500" width="750" />
<p>You can modify the tree using the Topiary Explorer java webstart (topiaryexplorer.jnlp) present in the main directory of this project and opening the tree_TC.tep file. See <a href="http://topiaryexplorer.sourceforge.net/user_guide/quickstart.html" target="_blank">Topiary User's Guide</a> for how to.</p>
	</section>

